{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_015NU1LvhfKAdVD19EY3RiCj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full pattern. The referral tests need `fundTestWallets()` and `initializeLocalnet()` because:\n1. `fundTestWallets()` gives the test wallets SOL (needed for wallet connection + any on-chain interactions)\n2. `initializeLocalnet()` creates the platform config and coinflip config on the local validator (needed for the app to function)\n\nHowever, the referral system is entirely off-chain. The tests mainly need:\n- Backend running with referral routes + database with migration applied\n- Frontend SPA served\n- Wallet connection working\n- Auth (JWT) working\n\n\n- Both setup functions are still required since the wallet needs SOL to sign auth challenges and the app expects on-chain configs to exist\n\nNow I'm writing the referral test file with three main flows: verifying the referral page renders in an authenticated state, having one player set a referral code and confirm it displays in the URL, and testing when another player visits the referral link to verify the code gets captured.\n\nI'm also considering whether the existing smoke test adequately covers auth, and checking if the local E2E environment actually runs the referral migration before the backend starts. Looking at the run script, migrations do execute beforehand, so the referral tables should be available.\n\nSince the local E2E tests use an isolated database schema, I don't need to worry about test code conflicts. Now I'm ready to write the test that covers the core referral flows.\n\nWriting the E2E test... Defining selectors for the referral UI components...\n\nNow I'm setting up a helper function that waits for authentication to complete after navigation, since the single-page app re-authenticates on each full page load, and then starting the test suite for the referral system.\n\nSetting up test fixtures... Writing test assertions...\n\nNow I'm setting up the second part of the test where Player B navigates to the referral link and the auto-apply mechanism should trigger automatically, verifying the API call completes successfully and redirects properly.\n\nNow I'm verifying that Player B's profile shows the referral connection by navigating to settings, waiting for the profile to load, and checking that the \"Referred by:\" text appears in the referral section.\n\nNext, Player A needs to refresh the referrals page and confirm the count shows 1 referred player by checking the stats values.\n\nNow I'm thinking through a potential issue with the auto-apply flow—when Player B hits the referral link, the code gets stored and redirects to home, then auth happens, and `useReferralApply` should fire. The timing concern is whether `waitForResponse` needs to be set up before the navigation triggers the apply request, since the flow happens quickly during the redirect sequence. , the URL is still `/r/e2e-ref-test` since the `goto` resolves before React Router's client-side redirect kicks in. The `waitForURL` will catch the navigation to `/` in step 7, and `applyPromise` will resolve when the referral apply call completes. I'm going to stick with the `waitForURL` approach since Playwright should properly handle the full URL including the domain when matching against the regex pattern. I'm realizing the function approach with `new URL(url).pathname === \"/\"` is cleaner than trying to match glob patterns, but actually the simplest solution is to just wait for the header element to appear after navigation, since that indicates the page has fully loaded after the redirect.\n\nSetting up a response listener before navigating to the referral link lets me wait for the auto-apply call to fire and verify it succeeds with a 200 status. The `goto` returns once the page loads, then the apply request fires during React's lifecycle and resolves the promise.\n\nChecking for potential timing issues...\n\nthe `waitForResponse` listener is event-based and set up before `goto`, so it'll catch the response whenever it happens during or after navigation. Since the page object persists across navigations in Playwright, the listener should survive and catch the apply response.\n\nI'm also noticing this pattern is used elsewhere in the codebase, which gives me confidence it'll work. The main thing I need to verify is whether the apply call will actually fire—the hook checks for `isAuthenticated`, `accessToken`, and `address` before making the request, so I should make sure those conditions are met.\n\nI think the test structure is solid. I should add coverage for the sidebar navigation link since that's a visible UI element that changes. For the manual apply flow, I could test Player A applying their own code to validate error handling, but the primary user flow I need to cover is the core path: setting a code, sharing it, having a friend apply, and seeing the stats update.\n\nBoth `fundTestWallets()` and `initializeLocalnet()` are worth including—the wallet funding is essential for auth, and while the referral page itself doesn't query on-chain data, the app shell likely needs those configs to render properly. I'll follow the pattern of the other local E2E tests and include both.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out the final test file.\n\nActually, let me verify the `waitForAuth` pattern works as expected. Setting up the listener before `goto` is fine—it'll be ready to catch the auth requests once navigation triggers and React boots up.\n\nFor Player B's flow through `/r/e2e-ref-test`, the auth happens after the redirect, so I should still set up the listener beforehand, though I mainly need to wait for the apply call to complete rather than explicitly tracking auth.\n\nWriting the test structure... Writing the referral test flow... Writing test assertions...\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the `waitForResponse` logic for the auto-apply flow. The `useReferralApply` hook depends on `isAuthenticated`, `accessToken`, and `address` becoming truthy, then it reads the referral code from localStorage and applies it. Since `ReferralCapture` writes to localStorage before the navigation happens, I need to verify the timing is correct.\n\nActually, there's a potential issue with the useEffect dependency array and when exactly the hook fires relative to the redirect.\n\nThe flow is: AppContent renders at `/`, then WalletProvider and SessionContext initialize asynchronously, and only once `isAuthenticated` becomes true does `useReferralApply` fire. So the apply call happens after auth completes, which is what I want. My `waitForResponse` setup should catch the response, but I need to verify that if the backend rejects the apply (like if the player already has a referrer), the promise still resolves so my status assertion can catch the failure.\n\nThe real issue is whether the test DB stays clean between runs. The E2E tests use a separate schema, but if the referral code \"e2e-ref-test\" already exists from a previous run, the second run would fail because the code is UNIQUE in the database. However, `upsertReferralCode` should replace the existing code for the same wallet, so I need to check how the DB actually handles this constraint. Looking at how other tests handle this, they don't clean up between runs either, so the local E2E runner probably handles database state automatically. I'll write the test following the existing patterns and let any DB state issues surface when it actually runs. Though I should account for the fact that `waitForResponse` for `/referral/apply` might never fire if the user is already linked from a previous test run, which would cause a timeout—I need to add a safeguard for that scenario.\n\nInstead of waiting for a specific API response, I could make this more robust by navigating to the referral link, waiting for the wallet to connect, giving the apply hook time to execute, then checking the profile settings to verify the referrer was set. It's less precise but handles the case where the apply call doesn't happen. I'm working through the best way to structure this check without introducing flaky timing dependencies.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to use `waitForResponse` to listen for the apply endpoint and add a comment explaining that the test assumes a clean database state, which is standard for local E2E tests. I should also consider the edge case where Player A already has a referral code set—the upsert should replace it, so repeat runs should work fine. For Player B, if they're already linked to Player A, the API would return a 409 ALREADY_LINKED error, which I need to handle.\n\nLooking at the `useReferralApply` hook, it checks for authentication and a stored referral code before making the apply call. The hook doesn't verify the current referrer status beforehand, so the API call will fire regardless, and if Player B is already linked, it'll return an error that the hook treats as a permanent failure and clears localStorage.\n\nThe hook handles the response by checking for specific error patterns like ALREADY_LINKED or SELF_REFERRAL, and clears localStorage when it detects these permanent errors. So my `waitForResponse` will resolve, but I need to account for the fact that subsequent runs might return a 409 or other error code instead of a 200.\n\nI'm realizing that being too lenient with the status code check makes the test less strict. The cleaner approach is to expect a 200 and rely on the E2E runner's clean database state between runs, since other tests follow this same pattern. The referral code should work consistently because of the upsert logic, and if the DB isn't clean, the test will fail naturally and signal that something's wrong.\n\nNow I need to write out the full test file. The hook is properly exported from the barrel file, and it includes the `appliedRef` guard to prevent duplicate API calls even if the component re-renders. For the test, I need to make sure I'm waiting for exactly one `/referral/apply` response, and I'm confident the hook design supports that. Let me write the test now, though I should double-check how Playwright handles the response listener if no matching response arrives within the timeout.\n\nLooking at the existing profile-transactions test, they set up `waitForResponse` before calling `goto`, and it successfully catches the auth response that fires during navigation. So the listener persists across the page load and will catch the apply response when it fires.\n\nNow I'm ready to write the test. I'll keep everything in a single test function, and the serial mode is just a precaution for future tests. I'll also add a check for the sidebar navigation item to verify the state changed correctly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1162,"cache_read_input_tokens":77479,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1162},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"18302c5c-b9ec-4f75-9de3-1cbb537277bf","uuid":"9b752865-5461-429b-9585-60cab5df7af7"}
